{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"66e4b0d9-507c-468f-b97c-cd5ab23a1be5","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2**, which supports the modern approach. Here's the recommended pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    // TestContext is injected automatically via init property (MSTest 3.x+)\n    public TestContext TestContext { get; init; }\n\n    // Synchronous per-test initialization\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public void Setup()\n    {\n        // sync setup work\n    }\n\n    // Asynchronous per-test initialization\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        // async setup work (runs after sync Setup)\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void MyTest() { }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`TestContext`** — use `{ get; init; }` (no need for the old `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` pattern or constructor injection).\n- **Multiple `[TestInitialize]`** methods are supported in MSTest 3.x. Sync ones run first, then async ones.\n- For **class-level** one-time setup, use `[ClassInitialize]` (static) similarly.\n- `[TestCleanup]` works the same way for teardown.\n\nWant me to scaffold a test file in your project with this pattern?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a3d2ba3b-ae23-429d-87a5-1b2673ee62be","outputTokens":317,"requestId":"4C11:2BC959:BB522F:E99C4F:6A0131EB"},"id":"d69f24d6-d20b-41b9-b9b2-54eed7f985b3","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:33:38.719Z","parentId":"12dcd507-a964-4952-8dcc-e37b304d27b4"}
